T1  - The Criterion Approach to Unraveling Beta and Alpha Change
AU  - Van de Vliert, Evert
AU  - Huismans, Sipke E.
AU  - Stok, Jan J. L.
Y1  - 1985/04/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1985.4278187
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1985.4278187
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 269
EP  - 275
VL  - 10
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Three types of change that occur with self-reported pre-post-intervention data are reconceptualization (gamma change), scale recalibration (beta change), and actual increase or decrease (alpha II change). Beta change is shown to have occurred if a beta change criterion is theoretically and empirically related to the shifts in the focal variable. It is suggested that correlations between shifts on a criterion and a focal variable are a means for estimating the relative size of beta and alpha change.
AB  - Three types of change that occur with self-reported pre-post-intervention data are reconceptualization (gamma change), scale recalibration (beta change), and actual increase or decrease (alpha II change). Beta change is shown to have occurred if a beta change criterion is theoretically and empirically related to the shifts in the focal variable. It is suggested that correlations between shifts on a criterion and a focal variable are a means for estimating the relative size of beta and alpha change.
