T1  - Organizational Work and the Perceived Quality of Life: Toward a Conceptual Model
AU  - Rice, Robert W.
AU  - McFarlin, Dean B.
AU  - Hunt, Raymond G.
AU  - Near, Janet P.
Y1  - 1985/04/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1985.4278215
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1985.4278215
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 296
EP  - 310
VL  - 10
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A preliminary conceptual model for examining the effects of organizational work on the perceived quality of life (pQL) defines pQL as affective beliefs (hot cognitions) concerning the status of one's life. The potential influences of work on pQL are considered in terms of effects mediated by the perceived quality of work life versus those mediated by the perceived quality of nonwork life; person-changing versus environment-changing effects; and first-party versus second-party effects.
AB  - A preliminary conceptual model for examining the effects of organizational work on the perceived quality of life (pQL) defines pQL as affective beliefs (hot cognitions) concerning the status of one's life. The potential influences of work on pQL are considered in terms of effects mediated by the perceived quality of work life versus those mediated by the perceived quality of nonwork life; person-changing versus environment-changing effects; and first-party versus second-party effects.
