TY  - JOUR
T1  - Japanese Management: What About the “Hard” Skills?
AU  - Nonaka, Ikujiro
AU  - Johansson, Johny K.
Y1  - 1985/04/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1985.4277850
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1985.4277850
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 181
EP  - 191
VL  - 10
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Many writers on Japanese management emphasize the importance of ?soft? skill, staff, style, and superordinate goal factors in managing successful organizations. It is argued here that Japanese firms face turbulent environments, making the ?hard? factors of strategy, structure, and systems necessary for success. The idea of organizational learning is used to explain how Japanese firms' hard skills have equalled and sometimes surpassed those of Western firms, despite the limited professional education of Japanese managers.
AB  - Many writers on Japanese management emphasize the importance of ?soft? skill, staff, style, and superordinate goal factors in managing successful organizations. It is argued here that Japanese firms face turbulent environments, making the ?hard? factors of strategy, structure, and systems necessary for success. The idea of organizational learning is used to explain how Japanese firms' hard skills have equalled and sometimes surpassed those of Western firms, despite the limited professional education of Japanese managers.
